                <head>62. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On June 7 the Soviet Union transmitted to the Embassies of the United States, the
                    United Kingdom, and France in Moscow notes protesting “a series of dangerous
                    provocations” by the West Berlin police and “Fascistic elements” against the
                    German Democratic Republic. In particular the Soviet Union protested the firing
                    by West Berlin police into the Soviet Sector. In their June 25 reply the Western
                    powers stated that the West Berlin police were responding to shots fired by
                    Eastern zone guards attempting to stop refugees from fleeing the Soviet Sector
                    and noted that the difficulties in Berlin were due exclusively to East Berlin
                    authorities acting with the full consent of the Soviet Union. For texts of the
                    notes, see Department of State Bulletin, July 16, 1962, pages 97–99.</p>
            </div>
